    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i think i get the snowball thing, but it's still frustrating. it feels like there are these extra costs or things eating away at my payment before it even touches the principal. are there specific parts of the math or certain types of fees that specifically cause that drag?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're right, there are several factors that can erode your payment before it even makes a dent in the principal. One of the main culprits is the fees associated with your loan, which can include origination fees, late payment fees, and prepayment penalties. These fees can be like a group of goblins stealing your money, making it seem like your payment is being devoured by unnecessary expenses. \n\nAnother factor is the compounding interest, which can be a sneaky one. It's like a tiny, insidious goblin that's always lurking in the shadows, multiplying your interest charges and making it seem like your balance is growing faster than it actually is. \n\nAdditionally, some loans may have a \"fee-based\" interest calculation, where the interest is calculated based on the outstanding balance, plus any accrued fees. This can be like a vicious cycle, where the fees are added to the interest, which is then added to the balance, and so on. It's a bit like a never-ending game of musical chairs, where the fees and interest are constantly shifting the balance.\n\nIt's worth noting that some loans may have a \"flat fee\" interest calculation, where the interest is a fixed amount per month, regardless of",
